<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-594-125  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 594 125.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  Oct 25 1990 n1237 p26(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>It's a new life for insurance. (Royal Life Insurance)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Vowler, John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Microcomputers are at the hub of Royal Insurance's client serviceas part of the company's drive to stay competitive.andP;  The computersare being used to rewrite the company's databases to client-namerecords.andP;  The company, which sells insurance directly andindirectly through tied and independent agents, is using theclient database as an information source for its variousdivisions.andP;  The company has a quote system wherein its 50 branchoffices can get an on-line quote for potential customers, andproduce a policy acceptance print-out within minutes.andP;  The companyis shifting towards a microcomputer-based system rather than dumbterminals, although it is not sure whether agents will have to payfor the microcomputers and laser printers.andP;  The company's ITdepartment has an IBM 3090/500S mainframe and is developingsoftware to integrate the central mainframe with themicrocomputers.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Royal Insurance Company PLC (Equipment and supplies).andO;Topic:     MISManagement of EDPMicrocomputersMainframe ComputersInsurance IndustryData BasesStrategic PlanningCustomer Relations.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>